										<td colspan=2 valign="top">
										

  <center>
    <p><b><font size="5" face="verdana" color="gold">Character Creation</font></b></p>
    <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2">Creating a new character is 
      something that you will want to think about before you set foot inside the 
      world of EverQuest. There are many choices to be made between races and 
      classes. It can get very confusing to which one is best for you. It is recommended 
      to pick a class that you would have the most fun playing, depending on your 
      personality. For example, if you find yourself a nature loving person in 
      real life, then it would be best to become a druid or ranger and join the 
      ranks of nature's protectors. </font></p>
    <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2"> One of the aspects of creating 
      a new character that I stress is selecting a race that you like based on 
      appearance and role playing ability. Many people may preach about how race 
      plays a large impact in how you play. It is true that it can affect your 
      overall playing experience, as a high elf will be treated differently than 
      an ogre, but when people speak of race, they are mostly concerned with the 
      base stats they receive. You shouldn't really concern yourself with this 
      as they only play a minor role in younger levels. That extra bit of intelligence 
      the erudite has over the gnome, or the massive strength of an ogre towards 
      a half elf may seem like a big deal, but there are many items that you can 
      obtain to customize what your character needs are. </font> 
    <table border=0 width='100%' cellspacing=5 cellpadding=5>
      <tr> 
        
      <td><font color=gold size=2 face="verdana"><b>Classes</b></font></td>
        <td><font size="2" face=verdana color="gold"><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Important Tips</b></font></td>
      </tr>
      <tr> 
        <td valign=top width="17%"> 
          <p><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><a href="#1">Bard</a> 
            <br>
            <a href="#2">Cleric</a> <br>
            <a href="#3">Druid</a> <br>
            <a href="#4">Enchanter</a> <br>
            <a href="#5">Magician</a> <br>
            <a href="#6">Monk</a> <br>
            <a href="#7">Necromancer</a><br>
            <a href="#8">Paladin</a><br>
            <a href="#9">Ranger</a><br>
            <a href="#10">Rogue</a><br>
            <a href="#11">Shadow Knight</a><br>
            <a href="#12">Shaman</a><br>
            <a href="#13">Warrior</a><br>
            <a href="#14">Wizard</a></font> 
        </td>
        <td valign="top" width="83%"> 
          <ul>
            <li><font face="verdana" size="2">Pick a race and class that suits 
              your personality--something you can relate to or can role-play.</font> 
            <li><font face="verdana" size="2">Never pick a race based on the base 
              stat points; it's always best to create something you like based 
              on appearance and role playing ability.</font> 
            <li><font face="verdana" size="2">Remember there are many items and 
              spells throughout Norrath that can further customize your character 
              stats. </font></li>
            <li><font face="verdana" size="2">Your character's name may be the 
              most important part of your character, so spend some time thinking 
              of a good one.</font></li>
            <li><font face="verdana" size="2">Experiment with different classes 
              and races till you find something that is right for you. However, 
              don't give up on your characters so easily; stick with them and 
              see how far you can make it.</font></li>
          </ul>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <p align="left"> <font color="gold" face="verdana" size="2"><b>Magic Vs Melee</b></font><font face="verdana" size="2"><br>
      <br>
      </font>
    <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2"> One of the largest choices 
      you will make while in the process of creating a character is choosing a 
      class which has magic abilities or one that does not. Then there is also 
      the choice of going with a pure caster over a hybrid one. </font> 
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Pure Melee</b><br>
      Strong, Powerful, and Deadly. They are the warriors, the pure fighters of 
      Norrath. People call them tanks, as that is what they are. Taking the most 
      damage, and dishing out massive blows is what the warrior is all about. 
      Being able to wear the best armors and wield powerful swords will allow 
      you to stand up against the strongest foes. </font>
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Pure Casters</b><br>
      They harness the true, raw power of magic and use it as a form of offense... 
      ones that can strike down foes with calls of lightning or bursts of fireballs. 
      They are the wizards, magicians, enchanters and necromancers. Weaving the 
      magic of destruction is not an easy task--they tend to be frail and have 
      very few hitpoints. They cannot stand in battle for very long and prefer 
      to watch from afar, calling on their deadly forces to strike down opponents. 
      </font> 
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Priests</b><br>
      They are the healers of EverQuest; some call them the miracle workers. Having 
      the ability to restore ones health or restore the living is a great power--one 
      not to be reckoning with. Every party should have a healer, and as one you 
      will find you are a key player in the groups power which will allow you 
      to go far longer then without one. They are the clerics, druids, and shamans. 
      Without them, the rest could not survive. </font> 
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Hybrids</b><br>
      Some call them warriors, and some call them casters for they are ones who 
      dabble in both. Hybrids constitute a large collection of classes in EverQuest. 
      They are your rangers, shadowknights, paladins, and bards. Having the best 
      of both worlds comes at a high price. Being able to melee fairly well, take 
      the blows, and cast magic can become a very powerful addition to any party. 
      However, because they can also understand and cast magic, it takes a little 
      more time and experience to gain the levels as a pure class would. In the 
      long run some say it's worth it; a higher level paladin can make a huge 
      difference in a party rather than his cousin the warrior. </font> 
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b><font color="gold">General 
      Attribute Information</font></b><br>
      <br>
      Attributes are very important to how you play your character and most of 
      the times affect the final outcome of the battle. Each class is awarded 
      a certain amount of bonus stat points which can be Distributed through any 
      Attribute you wish. It is recommended you look at our class guides for further 
      information or place the points into the suggested areas of that class. 
      </font> 
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Strength</b><br>
      Strength (Bard, Monk, Paladin, Ranger, Rogue, Shadow Knight, Shaman, Warrior)<br>
      Influences your maximum and average damage ratios, the more strength you 
      have the more likely you will hit harder. Additional strength will let you 
      learn your offensive skills faster, and let you carry more weight. </font>
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Stamina</b> (Monk, Paladin, 
      Ranger, Warrior, All Casters)<br>
      Affects how many total hit points you have, and how long you will be able 
      to hold your breath under water.</font>
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Dexterity</b> (Monk, Ranger, 
      Rogue, Warrior)<br>
      Influences how often your weapon proc (spell) will engage, and how quickly 
      you learn weapon skills. Will also increase how much damage you hit with 
      bows, and how fast you learn rogue skills. </font>
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Agility</b> (Bard, Monk, 
      Paladin, Ranger, Rogue, Shadow Knight, Warrior, All Casters)<br>
      </font><font face="verdana" size="2">Increases your percentage in how difficult 
      it is to hit you, as well as how much damage you take when you are hit. 
      Also, affects how quickly you can learn some defensive skills. </font>
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Intelligence</b> (Enchanter, 
      Magician, Necromancer, Shadow Knight, Wizard)<br>
      Directly affects the amount of mana of magi classes, including bards and 
      shadow knights. Also affects how quickly you can learn many skills.</font>
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Wisdom</b> (Cleric, Druid, 
      Paladin, Ranger, Shaman)<br>
      Directly affects the amount of mana the priest classes have, including rangers. 
      Also affects how quickly you can learn many skills if your wisdom is higher 
      then intelligence.</font>
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>Charisma</b> (Bard, Enchanter, 
      Druid) <br>
      Affects amount you will be paid for goods by NPC merchants, and how much 
      they will pay you. Also effects saving throw on certain bard and enchanter 
      spells (charms in particular) </font> 
    <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2"><b><font color="gold">Name</font></b><br>
      <br>
      </font>
    <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2"> This is a very important part 
      in creating your character, as it will be the name that will be forever 
      known. You cannot change your name, and for this reason you should spend 
      some time thinking about it. A name is very special--it distinguishes you 
      from other players, and it should be original. Try and think of something 
      that will fit well with your character--don't go pulling names out of fantasy 
      books as those are widely used and does not show your creativity. Try and 
      pick a name that is short and not just random characters; something that 
      you can sound out and people can easily remember and type. If your creative 
      skills have failed, try running through the random name generator, then 
      modify a name that you find to make it even more original. </font> 
    <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b><font color="gold">Deity</font></b><br>
      <br>
      </font>
    <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2"> Whom your character worships 
      is something that will affect how others will view you, most importantly 
      other NPC characters and merchants. Some merchants will give you better 
      prices if you believe in the same deity as themselves, some may attack you 
      on the spot. Which deity you choose should be an important part of your 
      characters role-playing ability also. </font> 
    <p align="left"> 
    <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2"><a name="1"><font color="gold">Bard</font></a><br>
      <br>
      </font>
    <div align="left"> 
      <blockquote> 
        <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2">The Bard’s stock-in-trade 
          is his ability to play songs. His songs are actually spells of a sort, 
          and their magical affects last as long as the Bard continues to sing 
          and play the correct instrument. They have some passing knowledge of 
          the Warrior ways (mainly for self-defense), but their main focus is 
          always their art, and so they will never be as skillful as Warriors.</font></p>
        
      <p align="left"><font face="verdana" size="2"><img src="assets/interface/dot.gif" width="8" height="8"> 
        <a href="default.asp?dest=class/bard">Bard Creation/Play Guide</a><br>
